\fs36 1) Outline
\fs24 \

\fs28 You are to implement a prototype of program allowing people to play a version of the board game Cluedo on a desktop computer. If you have not heard of the game Cluedo before, don\'92t worry, a specification detailing what you need to do is provided and you may always consult the game manual or the Wikipedia description of Cluedo.\
\
You will design a solution using CRC cards and UML, and implement a solution using Java. Feel free to use the Umple tool for designing models and generating code. You may fully stay within Umple, or depart from the original Umple ethos of never editing the generated code by instead using the generated code as a starting point for your implementation.\
\
Hint: If letting Umple assist you for the implementation part appeals to you, note that you will have to develop a deeper acquaintance with Umple than Lab 1 was designed to achieve.\

\fs24 \

\fs36 2) Specification
\fs24 \

\fs28 What follows is a specification for a simplified version of Cluedo. Please bear this in mind whenever referring to the original manual or other sources. True to life, the specification may be incomplete or ambiguous in parts and in such cases you will have to make reasonable assumptions which you should then explicitly state in the assignment report.\

\fs24 \

\fs36 2.1) Objective\

\fs28 The \cf5 game\cf2  is a murder mystery played by three to \cf5 six\cf2  \cf5 players\cf2  who \cf6 move around\cf2  a \cf5 board\cf2  comprising \cf5 nine rooms\cf2 . The aim is to deduce the \cf5 murder circumstances\cf2 , i.e., who the \cf5 murderer\cf2  was, what \cf5 weapon\cf2  they used and in which \cf5 room\cf2  they committed the murder. The Cluedo\cf5  board \cf6 consists\cf2  of nine\cf5  rooms\cf6  laid out in a circular fashion\cf2 . The \cf5 centre space (the \'93Cellar\'94)\cf2  is \cf6 inaccessible\cf2  to \cf5 players\cf2 .\

\fs24 \

\fs36 2.2) Board\

\fs28 The \cf5 board\cf2  is \cf6 divided into a \cf5 grid\cf6  of \cf5 24x25 squares\cf2  of which \cf6 some are not accessible\cf2  and some (those within rooms) may optionally be \cf6 treated as a single location\cf2 .\
\
\cf5 Players\cf2  \cf6 move\cf2  on this \cf5 grid\cf2  and the prototype does not need to honour the fact that\cf6  \cf5 rooms\cf6  \cf2 are technically not \cf6 divided by grid cells\cf2  in the original game. The prototype furthermore does not need to account for the \'93secret passages\'94 (stairwell connections which connect rooms in opposite corners).\
\
There are \cf5 six starting\cf2  \cf5 squares\cf2  \cf6 located at the perimeter of the \cf5 board\cf2 . Each \cf5 starting square\cf2  \cf6 indicates\cf2  which \cf5 character\cf2  \cf6 starts at that \cf5 position\cf2 .\

\fs24 \

\fs36 2.3) Characters\

\fs28 There are \cf5 six characters\cf2 , \cf6 one of which (randomly selected for each game play) \cf2 is the \cf5 murderer\cf2 : \
\cf5 \'95 Miss Scarlett \'95 Colonel Mustard \'95 Mrs. White \'95 Mr. Green \'95 Mrs. Peacock \'95 Professor Plum.\
\cf2 \
Each \cf5 player\cf2  \cf6 assumes the role of one of these \cf5 characters\cf2 . \cf6 If there are less than six \cf5 players\cf6 , some of the \cf5 characters\cf6  will be unused\cf2 .\

\fs24 \

\fs36 2.4) Weapons\

\fs28 There are \cf5 six weapons\cf2  in the game, one of which is the \cf5 murder weapon\cf2 : \'95 \cf5 Candlestick \'95 Dagger \'95 Lead Pipe \'95 Revolver \'95 Rope \'95 Spanner \
\cf2 \
Each \cf5 weapon\cf2  is \cf6 initially placed in a \cf5 room\cf6  chosen at random, \cf2 such that \cf6 no two \cf5 weapons\cf6  are in the same \cf5 room\cf6 .\cf2 \

