\fs36 2.5) Rules\

\fs28 \cf5 Every\cf2  \cf5 character\cf2 , \cf5 weapon\cf2  and \cf5 room\cf2  is \cf6 represented\cf2  by a \cf5 card\cf2  in the game. \cf6 Before the \cf5 game\cf6  starts\cf2 , \cf6 one \cf5 character\cf6 , one \cf5 weapon\cf6 , and one \cf5 room\cf6  \cf5 card\cf6  are blindly selected at random\cf2 . This \cf5 selection \cf6 represents\cf2  the \cf5 murder circumstances\cf2 , i.e., the \'93solution\'94 that players need to figure out during game play. The respective \cf5 cards\cf2  go into an \cf5 envelope\cf2  to be \cf6 hidden\cf2  from view.\
\
The remaining \cf5 weapon\cf2 , \cf5 room\cf2  and \cf5 character\cf2  \cf5 cards\cf2  are then \cf6 combined\cf2  into one \cf5 stack\cf2 , \cf6 shuffled and then dealt facedown evenly to \cf5 players\cf2 . Some \cf5 players\cf2  may \cf6 end up with more cards than others\cf2 . \cf5 Players\cf2  then take it in \cf5 turns\cf2  to \cf6 roll \cf5 two dice\cf2  and \cf6 move their character \cf5 token\cf2  a corresponding number \cf6 (sum of the dice values)\cf2  of \cf5 squares\cf2 . \cf6 Diagonal movement is not allowed\cf2  and \cf6 no space may be used twice during one turn\cf2 . When a \cf5 player\cf2  \cf6 enters\cf2  a \cf5 room\cf2 , they \cf6 do not need to use any remaining moves they have left\cf2 . They may then hypothesise about the murder circumstances by \cf6 making a \cf5 suggestion\cf2  which comprises the \cf5 room\cf6  \cf2 they are in, a \cf5 character\cf2  and a \cf5 weapon\cf2 . If the \cf5 character\cf2  and \cf5 weapon\cf2  named in the \cf5 suggestion\cf2  are \cf6 not in that room yet, they are now moved into the room\cf2 .\
\
When a \cf5 suggestion\cf2  is made, \cf6 \cb7 each \cf5 player\cf6 , in a \cb1 clockwise fashion, starting from the \cf5 current player\cf2 , attempts to \cf6 refute\cf2  the \cf5 suggestion\cf2 . A \cf5 suggestion\cf2  is \cf6 refuted by producing a \cf5 card\cf6  that matches one of the named murder circumstances\cf2  (as such a card cannot be in the solution envelope). A \cf5 refutation card\cf2  is only \cf6 shown\cf2  to the \cf5 player\cf2  that made the \cf5 suggestion\cf2 . If a \cf5 player\cf2  \cf6 has multiple refutation cards, it is their choice which one they pick\cf2 . \cf6 If no \cf5 player\cf6  can produce a \cf5 refutation\cf6 ,\cf2  the named \cf5 murder circumstances \cf2 are a potential \cf5 solution\cf2  \cf5 candidate\cf2  that \cf6 may or may not be used to make an \cf5 accusation\cf2  later on (by any player).\
\
An \cf5 accusation\cf2  comprises a \cf5 character\cf2 , a \cf5 weapon\cf2 , and a \cf5 room\cf2  (which can be any room, not just the one the player making the accusation may be in). If the \cf5 accusation\cf2  \cf6 made by a\cf2  \cf5 player\cf2  \cf6 exactly matches the actual \cf5 murder circumstances\cf2  \cf6 (only the accusing \cf5 player\cf6  is allowed to see the solution)\cf2  the \cf5 player\cf2  \cf6 wins\cf2 , \cf6 otherwise the \cf5 player\cf6  is excluded from making further \cf5 suggestions\cf6  or \cf5 accusations\cf2 . This means the \cf5 player\cf2  will \cf6 continue to refute suggestions by others but cannot win the game anymore\cf2 .\
